<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Avil Page (manipulate pdf)</title><link>http://www.avilpage.com</link><description></description><atom:link href="http://www.avilpage.com/categories/manipulate-pdf.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Thu, 18 Aug 2016 15:30:15 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>https://getnikola.com/</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>A Simple Way To Split &amp; Merge Multipage PDF Files With PDF Toolkit!</title><link>http://www.avilpage.com/2014/05/split-merge-stitch-pdf-file-ubuntu/</link><dc:creator>Chillar Anand</dc:creator><description>&lt;div dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;" trbidi="on"&gt;Sometimes we come across a situation where we need to scissor or stitch the pdf document. There are several tools to do this job. The simplest and easiest way is to use PDF Toolkit.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;This tutorial is for Geeks. If you are not one, go get &lt;a href="http://www.pdflabs.com/tools/pdftk-the-pdf-toolkit/pdftk_free-2.02-win-setup.exe" target="_blank"&gt;GUI App for windows&lt;/a&gt;Â  or if you just want to split one single file, use online tools like &lt;a href="http://www.splitpdf.com/" target="_blank"&gt;Split PDF&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I am going to split and stitch several pdf documents using pdftk &amp;amp; Ubuntu 12.04.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Lets first install it&lt;br&gt;&lt;div dir="ltr" trbidi="on"&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;pre style="box-sizing: border-box;"&gt;&lt;code class="bash hljs " style="background-color: #333333; border-bottom-left-radius: 6px; border-bottom-right-radius: 6px; border-top-left-radius: 6px; border-top-right-radius: 6px; box-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.298039) 0px 1px 2px inset, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.0980392) 0px 1px 0px, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.498039) 0px -1px 0px; box-sizing: border-box; display: block; padding: 8px; position: relative; text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="background-color: transparent; text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #eeeeee;"&gt;sudo apt-get install pdftk&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Now you are armed with tool kit, lets have some fun with it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;h3 style="text-align: left;"&gt;Splitting PDF:&lt;/h3&gt;Lets say you want to split the entire pdf into single pages, you can do that by&lt;br&gt;&lt;div dir="ltr" trbidi="on"&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;pre style="box-sizing: border-box;"&gt;&lt;code class="bash hljs " style="background-color: #333333; border-bottom-left-radius: 6px; border-bottom-right-radius: 6px; border-top-left-radius: 6px; border-top-right-radius: 6px; box-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.298039) 0px 1px 2px inset, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.0980392) 0px 1px 0px, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.498039) 0px -1px 0px; box-sizing: border-box; display: block; padding: 8px; position: relative; text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="background-color: transparent; text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #eeeeee;"&gt;pdftk myFile.pdf burst&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;If you want you can split only a specific page by using&lt;br&gt;&lt;div dir="ltr" trbidi="on"&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;pre style="box-sizing: border-box;"&gt;&lt;code class="bash hljs " style="background-color: #333333; border-bottom-left-radius: 6px; border-bottom-right-radius: 6px; border-top-left-radius: 6px; border-top-right-radius: 6px; box-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.298039) 0px 1px 2px inset, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.0980392) 0px 1px 0px, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.498039) 0px -1px 0px; box-sizing: border-box; display: block; padding: 8px; position: relative; text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="background-color: transparent; text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #eeeeee;"&gt;pdftk myFile.pdf cat 21 output page_21.pdf&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;You can also split specific set of pages by using&lt;br&gt;&lt;div dir="ltr" trbidi="on"&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;pre style="box-sizing: border-box;"&gt;&lt;code class="bash hljs " style="background-color: #333333; border-bottom-left-radius: 6px; border-bottom-right-radius: 6px; border-top-left-radius: 6px; border-top-right-radius: 6px; box-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.298039) 0px 1px 2px inset, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.0980392) 0px 1px 0px, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.498039) 0px -1px 0px; box-sizing: border-box; display: block; padding: 8px; position: relative; text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #eeeeee;"&gt;pdftk myFile.pdf cat  21-end output 21_to_last.pdf&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h3 style="text-align: left;"&gt;Merging PDF:&lt;/h3&gt;Now we have scissored a lot of pages. Lets go ahead and stitch a few of them.&lt;br&gt;Lets stitch the pdf's we have created in the previous steps.&lt;br&gt;&lt;div dir="ltr" trbidi="on"&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;pre style="box-sizing: border-box;"&gt;&lt;code class="bash hljs " style="background-color: #333333; border-bottom-left-radius: 6px; border-bottom-right-radius: 6px; border-top-left-radius: 6px; border-top-right-radius: 6px; box-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.298039) 0px 1px 2px inset, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.0980392) 0px 1px 0px, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.498039) 0px -1px 0px; box-sizing: border-box; display: block; padding: 8px; position: relative; text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #eeeeee;"&gt;pdftk page_21.pdf 21_to_end.pdf cat output stitched.pdf&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;This will stitch the two pdf's we created above.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;If you have a huge list of single age pdf's in a folder and if you want to stitch them together, change the current working directory to the required directory and use this&lt;br&gt;&lt;div dir="ltr" trbidi="on"&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;pre style="box-sizing: border-box;"&gt;&lt;code class="bash hljs " style="background-color: #333333; border-bottom-left-radius: 6px; border-bottom-right-radius: 6px; border-top-left-radius: 6px; border-top-right-radius: 6px; box-shadow: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.298039) 0px 1px 2px inset, rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.0980392) 0px 1px 0px, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.498039) 0px -1px 0px; box-sizing: border-box; display: block; padding: 8px; position: relative; text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #eeeeee;"&gt;pdftk *.pdf cat output newFile.pdf&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;This will stitch all the pdf in the current directory to a single pdf.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;These are few simple things to do with pdftk, if you want to dig deep into this &lt;a href="http://www.pdflabs.com/tools/pdftk-the-pdf-toolkit/" target="_blank"&gt;visit pdftk and explore it&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: inherit;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>manipulate pdf</category><category>pdf libraries</category><category>pdf splitter</category><category>pdf stitcher</category><category>pdftk</category><category>pdftoolkit</category><category>software to split pdf</category><category>split pdf into multiple files</category><category>stitch multiple pages into single pdf</category><category>tech</category><category>ubuntu tutorials tips tricks</category><guid>http://www.avilpage.com/2014/05/split-merge-stitch-pdf-file-ubuntu/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 07 May 2014 13:44:00 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>